    mplfinance¶

    I have decided to make a quick summary for myself after finishing one of my projects about getting live financial data. mplfinance is a powerful but easy-to-use library. It doesn't require much time to understand and can make professional financial charts in no time. This notebook has all of the most common functionalities of finance.

    Install libraries¶

    Install all the libraries that will be needed to plot financial charts

    • %matplotlib inline: inline matplotlib
    • pandas
    • mplfinance: a financial package of matplotlib

    Note: it might be necessary to install the library through !pip. If that is the case use !pip install mplfinance to install the package

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    %matplotlib inline
import pandas as pd

!pip install mplfinance
import mplfinance as mpf
    %matplotlib inline import pandas as pd !pip install mplfinance import mplfinance as mpf

    Create a reference and a dataframe from available the financial data. Apple's stock history between March 3, 2021 and March 3, 2022 will be used. The data sheet is saved under the name AAPL.csv. The data has been downloaded from yahoo fianance.

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Create a dataframe
file = '/content/AAPL.csv'

data = pd.read_csv(file)
    # Create a dataframe file = '/content/AAPL.csv' data = pd.read_csv(file)

    Start Plotting¶

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Simple plot
mpf.plot(data)
    # Simple plot mpf.plot(data)

    A volume bar chart can be easily added by setting a couple of parameters to the function.

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Plot chart with volume
mpf.plot(data, type='line', volume=True)
    # Plot chart with volume mpf.plot(data, type='line', volume=True)

    Let's plot only the data of a single month

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Plot only data from February 2022
mpf.plot(data['2022-02'], volume=True)
    # Plot only data from February 2022 mpf.plot(data['2022-02'], volume=True)

    By default it will plot a ohlc (for open-high-low-close) chart. The type of the chart can be specified by the keyword type. There are serveral type to plot such as:

    • ohlc: open-high-low-close chart as of above
    • candle: candlestick bar chart
    • line: a single line
    • renko: for a renko chart
    • pnf: point and figure chart

    Let's change the plot into a candlestick chart.

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Plot candlestick chart
mpf.plot(data['2022-02'], type='candle', volume=True)
    # Plot candlestick chart mpf.plot(data['2022-02'], type='candle', volume=True)
    /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:2: FutureWarning: Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` instead.

    Add Simple Styling¶

    There are several keywords that can be used such as

    • type: specify the chart type as stated above. Default as line
    • mav: moving average line. The line interval will adjust itself depending of the frequency of the data. Default as None
    • volume: show volume bar. Default as None
    • show_nontrading: hide or show the data from a non-trading period. Default as False

    Let's plot a candlestick chart with data in year 2022 with a moving average line and a volume bar chart.

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Plot
mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(10), volume=True)
    # Plot mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(10), volume=True)
    /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:2: FutureWarning: Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` instead.

    There are several paraemeters that can configure the chart's style for example;

    • title: add a title to the chart
    • figratio: aspect ratio in HxW of the chart. Be noted the the ratio must be between 0.2 and 5.0
    • tight_layout: removing the gaps between both side chart. Default as False
    • style: theme of the chart which affects the bar/line color, bg color, text size, etc.
    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, 
         title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, style='yahoo')
    mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, style='yahoo')
    /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:1: FutureWarning: Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` instead.

    Create Custom Styling¶

    What if to customize your own style?

    mpfinance style is made of 3 parts

    • marketcolors: is a mandatory parameter to set up the ups and downs color of the ohlc and volumn bars
    • mavcolors: (optional) to set the mav lines
    • matplotlib style: (optional) to alter the default Matplotlib style sheets (see more here)

    Two create a custome style 2 finctions will be called. make_marketcolors is to set up the style colors and make_mpf_style to define a style.

    Let's make simple changes of the candlestick chart.

    As a start, as the following is only to specify the ups and downs bar with the color green and red.

    For all other values that hasn't been specified will have the default values of matplotlib.

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Change up and down color
mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red')

# Define the custom style
s  = mpf.make_mpf_style(marketcolors=mc)
    # Change up and down color mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red') # Define the custom style s = mpf.make_mpf_style(marketcolors=mc)
    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, 
         title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, 
         style=s)
    mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, style=s)
    /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:1: FutureWarning: Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` instead.
  """Entry point for launching an IPython kernel.

    The function make_marketcolors can alter the color for the lines and bars through the following keywords;

    • up: set color of the upward bars
    • down: set color of the downward bars
    • edge: set the edge colors of the upward and downward bars
    • wick: list of colors to set the wick of the up and down bars. ex: {'up': 'blue', 'down': 'orange'}
    • volume: set the color of the volume bar
    • ohlc: set the color of the ohlc chart
    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Set style
mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red', edge="pink",
                           wick={'up': 'blue', 'down': 'orange'},
                           volume='yellow', ohlc='brown')
s  = mpf.make_mpf_style(marketcolors=mc)

# Plot chart with new style
mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, 
         title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, 
         style=s)

mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='ohlc', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, 
         title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, 
         style=s)

    There is also a way to inherit the colors from up and down to the volume bar and ohlc chart by using the string inherit or part if it i in etc.

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Set style
mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red', 
                           edge="inherit",
                           wick='in',
                           volume='inh', ohlc='inhe')
s  = mpf.make_mpf_style(marketcolors=mc)

# Plot chart with new style
mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, 
         title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, 
         style=s)
    # Set style mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red', edge="inherit", wick='in', volume='inh', ohlc='inhe') s = mpf.make_mpf_style(marketcolors=mc) # Plot chart with new style mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, style=s)
    /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:9: FutureWarning: Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` instead.
  if __name__ == '__main__':

    make_mpf_style() is to define a custom style. The following keywords are available

    • base_mpf_style: str name of a mpf style.
    • base_mpl_style: str name of a matplotlib style.
    • marketcolors: output from make_marketcolors()
    • mavcolors: list of the moving average line
    • facecolor: facecolor of the axes
    • edgecolor: edge color of the axes
    • figcolor: facecolor of the figure outside the axes
    • gridcolor: grid lines color
    • gridstyle: grid line styles: - for solid lines, -- for dashed lines, : for dotted lines, None or for no lines
    • gridaxis: lines to be drawn horizontal axes, vertical axes, or both axes
    • y_on_right: bool display y-axes labels on the right
    • rc: dict of rcParam to be specified
    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Set custom colors
mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red', inherit=True)
# Set style
s  = mpf.make_mpf_style(marketcolors=mc, facecolor='grey', gridcolor='white',
                        gridstyle='-', gridaxis='both')

# Plot chart with new style
mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, 
         title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, 
         style=s)
    # Set custom colors mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red', inherit=True) # Set style s = mpf.make_mpf_style(marketcolors=mc, facecolor='grey', gridcolor='white', gridstyle='-', gridaxis='both') # Plot chart with new style mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, style=s)
    /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:8: FutureWarning: Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` instead.

    It can also inherit a whole matplotlib base styles (not mpf style) with the keyword base_mpl_style or mpf style with the keyword base_mpf_style.

    • Full list of matplotlib style here
    • Full list of mpf style here

    The example below will use a mpf style with our custom style

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Set custom colors
mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red', inherit=True)
# Set style
s  = mpf.make_mpf_style(base_mpf_style='mike', marketcolors=mc)

# Plot chart with new style
mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, 
         title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, 
         style=s)
    # Set custom colors mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(up='green',down='red', inherit=True) # Set style s = mpf.make_mpf_style(base_mpf_style='mike', marketcolors=mc) # Plot chart with new style mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, style=s)
    /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:7: FutureWarning: Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` instead.
  import sys

    It is also possible to combine both style together.

    The following example will combine the seaborn matplotlib style and the mike mpf style

    In [ ]:
    Copied! 
    # Set style
mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(base_mpf_style='mike')
s  = mpf.make_mpf_style(base_mpl_style='seaborn', marketcolors=mc)

# Plot chart with new style
mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, 
         title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, 
         style=s)
    # Set style mc = mpf.make_marketcolors(base_mpf_style='mike') s = mpf.make_mpf_style(base_mpl_style='seaborn', marketcolors=mc) # Plot chart with new style mpf.plot(data['2022'], type='candle', mav=(5, 10), volume=True, title='Apple Inc. 2022', figratio=(12, 8), tight_layout=True, style=s)
    /usr/local/lib/python3.7/dist-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:6: FutureWarning: Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` instead.
